Arrington draws on her extensive fieldwork to illustrate these dynamics through comparisons of the parallel Japanese and South Korean movements of victims of harsh leprosy control policies, blood products tainted by hepatitis C, and North Korean abductions. Her book thereby highlights how citizens in Northeast Asia—a region grappling with how to address Japan’s past wrongs—are leveraging similar processes to hold their own governments accountable for more recent harms. Accidental Activists also reveals the growing power of litigation to promote policy change and greater accountability from decision makers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aGovernment liabilityzJapan. 0aGovernment liabilityzKorea (South). 0aPolitical participationzJapan. 0aPolitical participationzKorea (South). 0aVictimsxPolitical activityzJapan. 0aVictimsxPolitical activityzKorea (South). 4aAsian Studies. 4aPolitical Science & Political History.  arights litigation, East Asia, government wrongdoing, redress, political elites, democratic policymakers, activism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Packagez978311064982608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066749340uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170337940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501703379423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501703379/original  a978-3-11-064982-6  Asian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Package  a978-3-11-066749-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles